 <body> 
  <p>We.Retail has been built with a globalized site structure offering a language masters that can be live-copied to country-specific web sites. Everything is set up out-of-the-box to allow you to experiment with this structure and the built-in translation capabilities.</p> 
  <h2>Trying it out</h2> 
  <ol> 
   <li><p>Open the sites console from <strong>Global Navigation -&amp;gt; Sites</strong>.</p> </li> 
   <li><p>Switch to column view (if not already active) and select We.Retail. Note the example country structure with Switzerland, the United States, France, etc., along side the Language Masters.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-99.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Select Switzerland and see the language roots for the languages of that country. Note that there is not yet any content below these roots.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-100.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Switch to the list view and see that the language copies for the countries are all live copies.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-101.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Return to column view and click on the Language Master and see the language master roots with content. Note that only English has content.</p> <p>We.Retail does not come with any translated content, but the structure and configuration is in place to allow you to demonstrate the translation services.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-102.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>With the English Language Master selected, open the <strong>References</strong> rail in the sites console and select <strong>Language Copies</strong>.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-103.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Tick the checkbox next to the <strong>Language Copies</strong> label to select all language copies. In the <strong>Update language copies</strong> section of the rail, select the option to <strong>Create a new translation project</strong>. Provide a name for the project and click <strong>Update</strong>.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-104.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>A project is created for each language translation. View them under <strong>Navigation -&amp;gt; Projects</strong>.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-105.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Click on German to see the details of the translation project. Note that the status is in <strong>Draft</strong>. To start the translation with Microsoft's translation service, click the chevron next to the <strong>Translation Job</strong> heading and select <strong>Start</strong>.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-106.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>The translation project starts. Click on the ellipsis at the bottom of the card labeled Translation Job to see the details. Pages with the state <strong>Ready for review</strong> have already been translated by the translation service.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-107.png" /></li> 
   <li><p>Selecting one of the pages in the list and then <strong>Preview in Sites</strong> in the toolbar opens the translated page in the page editor.</p> <img imageRotate="0" src="assets/chlimage_1-108.png" /></li> 
  </ol> 
  <note> 
   <p>This procedure demonstrated the built-in integration with Microsoft machine translation. Using the <a href="../../../sites/administering/using/translation.md">AEM Translation Integration Framework</a>, you can integrate with many standard translation services to orchestrate the translation of AEM.</p> 
  </note> 
  <h2>Further Information</h2> 
  <p>For further information, refer to the authoring document <a href="../../../sites/administering/using/translation.md">Translating Content for Multilingual Sites</a> for complete technical details.</p> 
